org.whizu.jquery

Interface JQuery

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Content

    public interface JQuery
extends Content
    A jQuery object contains a collection of Document Object Model (DOM) elements that have been created from an HTML string or selected from a document. Since jQuery methods often use CSS selectors to match elements from a document, the set of elements in a jQuery object is often called a set of "matched elements" or "selected elements".
    See Also:
    jQuery's jQuery object

    • Method Detail

      • addClass

        JQuery addClass(java.lang.String clazz)
        Adds the specified classes to each of the set of matched elements. It's important to note that this method does not replace a class. It simply adds the class, appending it to any which may already be assigned to the elements. More than one class may be added at a time, separated by a space, to the set of matched elements, like so: 
         jQuery(this).addClass("myClass yourClass");
        See Also:
        jQuery's .addClass()

      • append

        JQuery append(java.lang.String... content)
        Insert content, specified by the parameter, to the end of each element in the set of matched elements. The .append() method inserts the specified content as the last child of each element in the jQuery collection.
        See Also:
        jQuery's .append()

      • prepend

        JQuery prepend(java.lang.String content)
        Insert content, specified by the parameter, to the beginning of each element in the set of matched elements. The .prepend() method inserts the specified content as the first child of each element in the jQuery collection.
        See Also:
        jQuery's .prepend()
